This paper focuses on the analysis of workers' earnings on Amazon Mechanical Turk, which is a platform for online crowd work. The study involves recording the performance of workers and analyzing the characteristics of tasks and working patterns that yield higher hourly wages. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, as it deals with the interaction between workers and the platform. Additionally, the paper involves data analysis and modeling, which could fall under the Cybernetics (cs.CY) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the design of the platform and worker tools, which could be relevant to the Computer Engineering (cs.CE) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves exploring the characteristics of tasks and working patterns, which could be relevant to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category.
